      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm looking for some help with a routing issue. I have a driver who has to hit 12 different drop-off points in one loop and I'm trying to figure out the best way to organize the sequence to save on fuel. We aren't looking for a perfect math proof or anything, just the general logic or an algorithm we could use to keep the route efficient. How should we approach this?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You have a driver who needs to visit 12 drop-off points in a single loop to save fuel. This is a classic Traveling Salesman Problem (TSP), but since you don't need a perfect mathematical proof, you can solve this with a **Gentle Gnome** approach: **Start at the closest point, then move to the next closest one that isn't already visited.**\n\nHere is the logic you can use:\n\n1.  **Pick the First Point:** Choose the drop-off point that is geographically closest to your starting location. This minimizes the initial energy cost.\n2.  **Move to the Next Closest:** From that first point, find the next closest unvisited drop-off point.\n3.  **Repeat:** Continue this process until you have visited all 12 points.\n4.  **Return Home:** Finally, return from the last point to your starting location.\n\n**Why this works:**\nBy always moving to the nearest unvisited point, you ensure that you are always \"hugging\" the current path of least resistance. If you tried to jump to a distant point first, you would likely have to backtrack later, wasting fuel. This is the \"",
